# Load the Wage dataset
data(Wage)

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(2024)

# Create 50/50 train/test split
train_indices <- sample(1:nrow(Wage), size = nrow(Wage) * 0.5)
wage_train <- Wage[train_indices, ]
wage_test <- Wage[-train_indices, ]

# Build a very complex (unpruned) tree
# Set cp = 0 (no pruning at all)
# Use default minsplit = 20 for more manageable tree size
tree_unpruned <- rpart(wage ~ age + education + jobclass + health_ins + maritl,
                       data = wage_train,
                       method = "anova",
                       control = rpart.control(cp = 0))

# Print the complexity parameter table
printcp(tree_unpruned)

Answers:

  • How many terminal nodes (leaves) does this unpruned tree have?
    The unpruned tree has 122 terminal nodes.

  • Does this tree look interpretable?
    With 122 leaves, the tree is getting quite complex. While more manageable than an extremely deep tree, it’s still more complex than we’d want for easy interpretation and communication to stakeholders.

  • Do you think this tree is overfitting? Why or why not?
    Yes, this tree is likely overfitting. With cp = 0, the tree continues to split until it reaches the minimum node size (default minsplit = 20), creating increasingly specific rules for the training data. We’ll need to examine the cross-validation results to find the optimal level of complexity.

Answers:

  • As the number of splits increases, what happens to the training error (rel error)?
    The training error (rel error) continuously decreases as we add more splits. This makes sense because a more complex tree can fit the training data better.

  • What happens to the cross-validation error (xerror)?
    The cross-validation error initially decreases as we add splits (the tree is learning useful patterns), but then it starts to increase or plateau after a certain point, indicating overfitting.

  • At what point does xerror start increasing? What does this suggest?
    The xerror reaches its minimum at around 10 splits. After this point, additional splits increase xerror, suggesting the tree is fitting noise in the training data rather than learning generalizable patterns.

Part 2: Visualizing Cross-Validation Results (10 minutes)

Task 2.1: Plot CV Error vs Tree Size

## CP with minimum xerror: 0.005871078
## CP using 1-SE rule: 0.0132036
## Number of splits with minimum xerror: 10
## Number of splits with 1-SE rule: 4

Answers:

  • What is the optimal CP value based on minimum xerror?
    The optimal CP based on minimum xerror is 0.005871.

  • What is the optimal CP value using the 1-SE rule?
    The optimal CP using the 1-SE rule is 0.013204.

  • Why might we prefer the 1-SE rule over just choosing the minimum?
    The 1-SE rule chooses a simpler model (fewer splits) whose CV error is within 1 standard error of the minimum. This is preferred because:

    • CV error has uncertainty, so models within 1 SE are statistically similar
    • Simpler models are more interpretable
    • Simpler models are more stable and less prone to overfitting
    • Simpler models generalize better to new data

Task 2.2: Understanding the 1-SE Rule

The 1-SE rule is a heuristic that says:

“Choose the simplest model whose error is within 1 standard error of the best model.”

Why?

  • Cross-validation error estimates have uncertainty
  • A simpler model with similar CV error is often better
  • Reduces overfitting and improves interpretability
  • More stable predictions on new data

  • Which model performs better on the test set?
    The pruned model performs better with a test MSE of 1335.1 compared to 1382.6.

  • Is the difference in test MSE substantial?
    No, the difference is relatively small (less than 5%), suggesting both models generalize similarly.

  • Did we sacrifice much accuracy by pruning?
    No! The pruned model has similar (or better) test performance while being much simpler. Notice the training MSE increased (from 868.87 to 1050.24), which is expected and actually good—it means we’re not overfitting as much.

  • Which model would you prefer to present to stakeholders? Why?
    The pruned model is strongly preferred because:

    • It has 11 leaves vs 122, making it far more interpretable
    • It achieves similar or better test performance
    • It’s easier to explain decision rules
    • Simpler models are more trustworthy and maintainable in production

    The optimal CP varies somewhat across seeds (SD = 0.001522), showing that the exact pruning threshold depends on the train/test split.

  • How consistent is the number of leaves?
    The number of leaves is relatively consistent (mean = 20.2, SD = 6.76), suggesting that cross-validation consistently identifies similarly-sized optimal trees.

  • How consistent is the test MSE?
    Test MSE shows some variation (CV = 5.99%), which is expected since different train/test splits will perform differently.

  • Is pruning helping with the variance problem?
    Pruning helps reduce variance compared to unpruned trees, but single trees still show instability across different data splits. This motivates the need for ensemble methods (coming next!).

Reflection Questions

For Discussion or Written Response:

1. Cross-Validation Benefits:

Cross-validation helps us avoid overfitting by evaluating our model on data it hasn’t seen during training. Unlike training error (which always decreases with complexity), CV error shows us when additional complexity stops helping generalization and starts hurting it. This gives us an honest estimate of how the model will perform on new data.

2. The 1-SE Rule:

The 1-SE rule recognizes that CV error estimates have uncertainty. Models within 1 standard error of the minimum are statistically indistinguishable in performance. By choosing the simplest model in this range, we get benefits of:

  • Better interpretability
  • Faster predictions
  • More stable results
  • Reduced risk of overfitting

It’s a principled way to favor parsimony. In our solution, we used the minimum CV error approach for simplicity and to maximize predictive accuracy, but the 1-SE rule is an excellent alternative when interpretability is paramount. In practice, you can compare both approaches to see which produces a more suitable model for your application.

3. Pruning vs Building:

I prefer approach (a): build full tree then prune. Reasons:

  • You can see the full cp table and make informed decisions
  • plotcp() gives you visual insight into the tradeoff
  • You can easily compare different pruning strategies
  • The computational cost is minimal for most datasets

However, approach (b) is more efficient for very large datasets.

4. Interpretability Gains:

The pruned tree (11 nodes) is dramatically more interpretable than the unpruned tree (122 nodes). With the pruned tree, I can:

  • Explain all decision rules in a single page
  • Walk through examples with stakeholders
  • Identify which factors matter most
  • Build trust through transparency

This is a huge win for model adoption and trustworthiness.

5. Remaining Limitations:

Even with optimal pruning, single trees are unstable—small changes in data lead to very different trees. Solutions:

  • Bagging: Average predictions from many trees trained on bootstrap samples
  • Random Forests: Bagging + random feature selection to decorrelate trees
  • Boosting: Sequentially build trees that correct previous errors

These ensemble methods dramatically reduce variance while maintaining (or improving) accuracy!

Key Takeaways

✓ Cross-validation provides honest estimates of model performance
✓ The complexity parameter (cp) controls tree size via cost-complexity pruning
✓ Using minimum CV error to select optimal cp (with 1-SE rule as alternative)
✓ Pruning dramatically improves interpretability without sacrificing accuracy
✓ Visualizing CV error helps understand the bias-variance tradeoff
✓ Even optimal single trees have high variance → need ensembles!
✓ Always evaluate on test data to get honest performance estimates

Next steps: We’ve optimized a single tree, but it’s still unstable. Time to learn about ensemble methods (bagging, random forests, and boosting) that combine many trees to reduce variance and improve predictions!
